Here is a sample implementation of a function that finds the shortest path in a non-looping graph in Java:

```
public static int shortestPath(String[] array) {
    int n = Integer.parseInt(array[0]);
    Map<String, List<String>> graph = new HashMap<>();
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        String node = array[i];
        graph.put(node, new ArrayList<>());
    }
    for (int i = n + 1; i < array.length; i++) {
        String[] nodes = array[i].split("-");
        graph.get(nodes[0]).add(nodes[1]);
        graph.get(nodes[1]).add(nodes[0]);
    }
    Queue<String> queue = new LinkedList<>();
    Set<String> visited = new HashSet<>();
    Map<String, String> parent = new HashMap<>();
    queue.offer(array[1]);
    visited.add(array[1]);
    while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
        String node = queue.poll();
        if (node.equals(array[n])) {
            List<String> path = new ArrayList<>();
            path.add(node);
            while (parent.containsKey(node)) {
                node = parent.get(node);
                path.add(node);
            }
            Collections.reverse(path);
            return path.size() - 1;
        }
        for (String neighbor : graph.get(node)) {
            if (!visited.contains(neighbor)) {
                queue.offer(neighbor);
                visited.add(neighbor);
                parent.put(neighbor, node);
            }
        }
    }
    return -1;
}
```

Here's how it works:

1. We first parse the input array to extract the number of nodes (n) and initialize a hash map to represent the graph. We also add each node to the graph as a key with an empty list as the value.

2. We then loop through the remaining elements of the array, which represent the edges between nodes, and add each edge to the graph by adding the second node as a neighbor of the first node and vice versa.

3. We use a breadth-first search (BFS) algorithm to find the shortest path between the first and last nodes. We start by adding the first node to a queue and marking it as visited. We also initialize a parent map to keep track of the parent node of each visited node.

4. We then loop through the queue until it's empty or we find the last node. For each node in the queue, we check if it's equal to the last node. If so, we reconstruct the path by following the parent map from the last node to the first node and return its length.

5. If the current node is not the last node, we loop through its neighbors in the graph that haven't been visited yet, add them to the queue, mark them as visited, and update their parent in the parent map to the current node.

6. If we reach the end of the BFS loop without finding the last node, it means there's no path between the first and last nodes, so we return -1.

Note that this implementation assumes the input array is well-formed and doesn't perform any error checking. It also doesn't handle cases where the graph contains loops or self-edges. These limitations can be addressed by adding appropriate checks and error handling.

Here is a sample implementation of a function that solves the problem using only arrays in Java:

```
public static int shortestPath(String[] array) {
    int n = Integer.parseInt(array[0]);
    String[] nodes = new String[n];
    int[][] connections = new int[n][n];
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        nodes[i] = array[i + 1];
    }
    for (int i = n + 1; i < array.length; i++) {
        String[] edge = array[i].split("-");
        int node1 = indexOf(nodes, edge[0]);
        int node2 = indexOf(nodes, edge[1]);
        connections[node1][node2] = 1;
        connections[node2][node1] = 1;
    }
    int[] distances = new int[n];
    boolean[] visited = new boolean[n];
    distances[0] = 0;
    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        distances[i] = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
    }
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        int minNode = minDistance(distances, visited);
        if (minNode == -1) {
            break;
        }
        visited[minNode] = true;
        for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            if (connections[minNode][j] == 1 && !visited[j]) {
                int distance = distances[minNode] + 1;
                if (distance < distances[j]) {
                    distances[j] = distance;
                }
            }
        }
    }
    return distances[n - 1] == Integer.MAX_VALUE ? -1 : distances[n - 1];
}

private static int indexOf(String[] array, String node) {
    for (int i = 0; i < array.length; i++) {
        if (array[i].equals(node)) {
            return i;
        }
    }
    return -1;
}

private static int minDistance(int[] distances, boolean[] visited) {
    int min = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
    int minIndex = -1;
    for (int i = 0; i < distances.length; i++) {
        if (!visited[i] && distances[i] < min) {
            min = distances[i];
            minIndex = i;
        }
    }
    return minIndex;
}
```

Here's how it works:

1. We first extract the number of nodes (n) from the first element of the input array, create two arrays to represent the nodes and connections between them, and populate the nodes array with the nodes from the input array.

2. We loop through the remaining elements of the input array, which represent the edges between nodes, and add each edge to the connections array by setting the corresponding positions to 1 (indicating a connection).

3. We use Dijkstra's algorithm to find the shortest path between the first and last nodes. We start by initializing an array to hold the distances from the first node to each node in the graph (with the distance to the first node set to 0 and all other distances set to infinity), and a boolean array to represent which nodes have been visited so far.

4. We loop through the nodes of the graph and pick the one with the minimum distance that hasn't been visited yet. We break out of the loop if we reach the last node (which means we've found the shortest path).

5. For each unvisited neighbor of the current node, we compute the distance from the first node to the neighbor through the current node and update the neighbor's distance if it's shorter than its current distance.

6. After visiting all nodes, the distance array contains the shortest distances from the first node to all other nodes. We return the distance to the last node, or -1 if there's no path between the first and last nodes.

Note that this implementation assumes the input array is well-formed and doesn't perform any error checking. It also uses the naive approach of searching for the minimum distance node in each iteration of the loop, which can be optimized using a priority queue or a heap. Also, this implementation is not suitable for large graphs as its time complexity is O(n^2).

