C++ typedef is a keyword that allows you to create an alias for an existing type. It is similar to defining a variable but instead of defining a new variable, it defines a new name for an existing data type. This can be used to make code more readable by giving descriptive names to complex or frequently used types. It can also make code more portable and easily maintainable, as typedefs can be changed without changing the underlying code. Here's an example:

typedef int myInt;

Now, whenever we use "myInt" in our code, it will be treated as an integer. For instance,

myInt x = 5;
myInt y = 10;
myInt z = x + y;

In the above code, "myInt" is simply an alias for "int", and the code will behave as if "int" was used instead.

