boost::split_iterator is a class template provided by the Boost C++ Libraries. It is used to split a string into a sequence of substrings, where the splitting is determined by a delimiter character or a delimiter string. The class template is defined in the <boost/algorithm/string/split.hpp> header file.

The syntax for using boost::split_iterator is as follows:

```
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <boost/algorithm/string.hpp>

int main() {
    std::string str = "Hello,World,How,Are,You";
    std::vector<std::string> tokens;
    boost::split_iterator<std::string::const_iterator> it = boost::make_split_iterator(str, boost::first_finder(",", boost::is_iequal()));
    boost::split_iterator<std::string::const_iterator> end;
    for (; it != end; ++it) {
        tokens.push_back(boost::copy_range<std::string>(*it));
    }
    return 0;
}
```

Here, we first include the necessary headers, including `<boost/algorithm/string.hpp>` which provides the functions and classes for string splitting.

In the `main()` function, we define a string `str`, which we want to split into tokens (substrings) separated by a comma. We then declare a vector `tokens` to store the resulting substrings.

Next, we create an instance `it` of the `boost::split_iterator<std::string::const_iterator>` class using the `boost::make_split_iterator()` function. This function takes two arguments: the string to split (`str`), and a delimiter finder object that determines where to split the string.

The delimiter finder object in this example is created using the `boost::first_finder()` function, which takes two arguments: the delimiter string (",") and an optional predicate function (`boost::is_iequal()`) that performs case-insensitive comparison.

We also declare an `end` iterator, which points past the end of the sequence of substrings.

Finally, we iterate over the sequence of substrings using a for-loop, and for each substring we append it to the `tokens` vector using the `boost::copy_range<std::string>()` function, which converts the substring from an iterator range to a string.

This produces the desired result: the `tokens` vector contains the substrings "Hello", "World", "How", "Are", and "You".

