In order to handle and throw the custom exceptions, you can follow these steps:

1. Create a custom exception class that extends `Exception`.
2. Modify the methods to throw the custom exception class and handle any original exceptions with a try-catch block.

Here's your code with the custom exception class added and exception handling applied to the methods:

```java
// Custom Exception Class
class MyCustomException extends Exception {
    public MyCustomException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }
}

public class Chapter10Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            method1();
        } catch (MyCustomException e) {
            System.err.println(e.getMessage());
        }
    }

    private static void method1() throws MyCustomException {
        method2();
    }

    private static void method2() throws MyCustomException {
        method3();
    }

    private static void method3() throws MyCustomException {
        method4();
    }

    private static void method4() throws MyCustomException {
        method5();
    }

    private static void method5() throws MyCustomException {
        method6();
    }

    private static void method6() throws MyCustomException {
        try {
            java.io.File in = new java.io.File("somefile.txt");
            java.io.File out = new java.io.File("somefile2.txt");
            java.util.Scanner inFile = new java.util.Scanner(in);
            java.io.FileWriter outFile = new java.io.FileWriter(out);
        } catch (java.io.FileNotFoundException e) {
            throw new MyCustomException("File not found exception: " + e.getMessage());
        } catch (java.io.IOException e) {
            throw new MyCustomException("IO exception: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

Now, if an exception is detected, a custom exception with a specific message will be thrown and caught in the `main()` method, and the user is notified of the issue.

