If by "wrap" you mean the continuation of a line to the next line, then fscanf function in C language does not take into account the wrapping of lines in the input stream. It simply reads characters or values as specified by the format string, without regard to the layout of the input stream.

For example, if the input stream contains a line that is wrapped to the next line, the fscanf function will treat it as two separate lines, unless the format string specifies otherwise.

Here is an example of fscanf function reading an integer followed by a string from the standard input, without taking into account any wrapping of lines:

```
int num;
char str[50];
fscanf(stdin, "%d %s", &num, str);
```

This code will read an integer and a string separated by a space character from the input stream. It does not care if the integer and string are on the same line or on different lines, as long as they are separated by a space character. If the input stream contains a line that is wrapped to the next line, it will still be treated as two separate lines if there is no space character separating the integer and string.

